    <a title="Patricia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1165121-patricia"><img alt="Patricia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620668271p2/1165121.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/54557408?book_show_action=true">Apr 30, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Patricia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Patricia" href="/user/show/1165121-patricia">Patricia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780606200707" href="/book/show/1212604.Black_Rain">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1165121-patricia?shelf=japan">japan</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer54557408" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5238866202174940801">This is a beautiful and harrowing account of the bombing of Hiroshima. Ibuse&apos;s overt condemnations of violence are sparing; he lets his relentless catlog of horrors speak for itself. Ibuse&apos;s focus on Shigemura and his family focuses and shapes this account of massive suffering as he juxtaposes it with simple daily concerns and hopes. The account of Yasuko&apos;s failed marriage plans brings home the tragedy of lives deprived of fundamental hopes and expectations. The book also includes an understated</span>
  <span id="freeText5238866202174940801" style="display:none">This is a beautiful and harrowing account of the bombing of Hiroshima. Ibuse's overt condemnations of violence are sparing; he lets his relentless catlog of horrors speak for itself. Ibuse's focus on Shigemura and his family focuses and shapes this account of massive suffering as he juxtaposes it with simple daily concerns and hopes. The account of Yasuko's failed marriage plans brings home the tragedy of lives deprived of fundamental hopes and expectations. The book also includes an understated kind of heroism. While one of the most harrowing aspects of the novel is how people overwhelmed by catastrophe are limited in their ability to help each other, it also includes memorable accounts of when they do: for instance, a man who survives partly due to his wife's devoted attention and 80 pounds of peaches. Ibuse writes an unforgettable account of ordinary lives trying compass enormity.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5238866202174940801" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


