    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_911305040" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/911305040" />
    <a title="Aubrey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4119460-aubrey"><img alt="Aubrey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1472535045p2/4119460.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/911305040?book_show_action=true">May 14, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aubrey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aubrey" href="/user/show/4119460-aubrey">Aubrey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=japanese">japanese</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=translated">translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=antidote-think-twice-all">antidote-think-twice-all</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=person-of-everything">person-of-everything</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=4-star">4-star</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=r-goodreads">r-goodreads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=person-of-translated">person-of-translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=antidote-translated">antidote-translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4119460-aubrey?shelf=1-read-on-hand">1-read-on-hand</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer911305040" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2534738284608227488"><blockquote>
  <i>The mushroom cloud was really shaped more like a jellyfish than a mushroom. Yet it seemed to have a more animal vitality than any jellyfish, with its leg that quivered and its head that changed color as it sprawled out slowly toward the southeast, writhing and raging as though it might hurl itself on our heads at any moment. It was an envoy of the devil himself, I decided: who else in the whole wide universe would have presumed to summon forth such a monstrosity? Should I ever get away alive?</i></blockquote></span>
  <span id="freeText2534738284608227488" style="display:none"><blockquote>
  <i>The mushroom cloud was really shaped more like a jellyfish than a mushroom. Yet it seemed to have a more animal vitality than any jellyfish, with its leg that quivered and its head that changed color as it sprawled out slowly toward the southeast, writhing and raging as though it might hurl itself on our heads at any moment. It was an envoy of the devil himself, I decided: who else in the whole wide universe would have presumed to summon forth such a monstrosity? Should I ever get away alive? Would my family survive? Was I, indeed, on my way home to rescue them? Or was I seeking refuge for myself alone?</i>
</blockquote>I've read many a varied host of introductions in my day. None, I think, was ever so disrespectful of the material it purported to introduce than this one. It has the typical smug outlook of a white person commenting on the work of a person who is not white, coupled with apologist meanderings and a general dodging of the inherent context, historical moreso than cultural, of this book's composition. This is why I had the uncharacteristic reaction of glee upon noting an error in this translation, obvious enough on the level of grammar for even me to register: the translator introduced this book, and in doing so went so far in attempting to neuter the work's ramifications that it's a good thing this book's quality is perfectly capable of speaking for itself. For, while one could well argue that this genre is "slice of life", much like Alexievich's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/357486.Voices_from_Chernobyl_The_Oral_History_of_a_Nuclear_Disaster" title="Voices from Chernobyl The Oral History of a Nuclear Disaster by Svetlana Alexievich" rel="nofollow noopener">Voices from Chernobyl</a>, this is a slice of gangrene taken from the heart of a people during one of the most fearsome crimes humanity has ever committed against itself. As such, one wouldn't be wrong in reacting to this as one would to Ghibli's 'Grave of the Fireflies'. The important thing, though, is to acknowledge the piece as a whole; not purely literature, not purely tragedy, but purely human all the same.<blockquote>
  <i>As for the saké, the same thing happened in our neighborhood association as everywhere else—once it went on the ration, people who had never touched it before the war started drinking. A peculiar thing to happen.</i>
</blockquote>I've already compared this to Alexievich's work, and going along with this, the introduction, banal as it is, does mention the descriptive "polyphony, which is a good starting point if not a wholly reliable term to use as a guiding post. For all the terror and hardship and agonizing ignorance, there is a plot to this, which subverts the horror with a calming structure to the point that the emotions almost come in measured waves of day to day woes here, chaos there, the final denouments collapsing one on top of the other after a number of pages fitting of a good sized novel. In a word, this work is unique, antagonizing the border between fiction and non enough that it wouldn't be out of turn for some editions to be twice as long as mine due to added footnotes and other extant, explanatory material. It must be mentioned that information about the bomb was suppressed in Japan by US imperial forces, so there's no telling how much earlier, recounting events in the 1940's and not published till on the cusp of the 1970's, could have appeared as a recognition, a balm, or even a sense of closure to so many of the people who lived these pages and must live on in the aftermath of them. Ignorance is bliss, but in the world of trauma and propaganda, it is all too easy for a self to fall into enforced solitary to the point of literally eating away at the brain. Classic this book certainly is, and the author not having access to the necessary material for nearly a decade after the bombing is a war crime.<blockquote>
  <i>The trouble was that all of us, spiritually, were bound hand and foot, and fiercely suppressed every urge to express anxiety, let alone dissatisfaction. Such was the power of the state.<br /><br />["]They say it's not harmful to human beings."<br />If someone from the Health Department had said so, I supposed it was all right.</i>
</blockquote>I've mentioned in previous reviews my growing desensitization regarding scenes of gore or tragedy as portrayed in literature. As such, I should worn prospective readers that there are numerous unflinching descriptions of injuries of the literal flesh-peeling-off-the-bones variety rendered in the text. This can be especially brutal when juxtaposed with discussions of folklore and traditional holidays, so if you're looking to experience this work, be sure that you are suitably prepared. One thing this book is not is garish or grotesque or guilty of playing up the shock factor, so it would be unfair to the author, as well as the people he drew his material from, to go in without the proper mentality. It's the only way, in my mind, to pay respect in reading this work. In term of Japan's role in WWII, which is still rightfully a contentious topic today, this is neither the time nor the place. Whatever judgment is deserved, the US had no right to deal it out. A beam in the eye and all that jazz.<blockquote>
  <i>...I'd decided that I'd rather die somewhere else, of some proper disease that I could account for.</i>
</blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="2534738284608227488" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


