    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_935781375" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/935781375" />
    <a title="G.G." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20701854-g-g"><img alt="G.G." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1518560834p2/20701854.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/935781375?book_show_action=true">May 13, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="G.G." class="user" itemprop="url" name="G.G." href="/user/show/20701854-g-g">G.G.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9784770006950" href="/book/show/3407723-black-rain">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20701854-g-g?shelf=20th-century-novels">20th-century-novels</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20701854-g-g?shelf=japanese-literature">japanese-literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer935781375" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15380297724479711146">A beautifully crafted novel by a novelist who was born in Hiroshima and deploys his intimate knowledge of the layout of the city and the topography of the local area--right down to the train lines--to create this moving portrait of a people in shock, stolidly coping with the cataclysm that has been unleashed on them. <br/><br/>There are touches of dark humor, like this paragraph at the end of chapter 5. The narrator has survived the blast and with enormous difficulty struggled back to his home, which at t</span>
  <span id="freeText15380297724479711146" style="display:none">A beautifully crafted novel by a novelist who was born in Hiroshima and deploys his intimate knowledge of the layout of the city and the topography of the local area--right down to the train lines--to create this moving portrait of a people in shock, stolidly coping with the cataclysm that has been unleashed on them. <br /><br />There are touches of dark humor, like this paragraph at the end of chapter 5. The narrator has survived the blast and with enormous difficulty struggled back to his home, which at this point is still standing, though "at an angle of about fifteen degrees."<br /><blockquote>I went back to the smaller room and helped myself to the cold tea in the teapot, drinking from the spout. I rummaged in the medicine chest for something to put on my burned cheek, but there was nothing that could be used as an ointment. The full-length mirror lay broken on the floor. I glanced at the calendar with its message for the day. "Never say die," it said.</blockquote><br />In the background of the novel there is also a sustained critique of the arrogance, corruption, and sheer incompetence of what remained of the Imperial Japanese Army in 1945. They loot provisions from local companies (pp. 148-49), medicines and bandages from hospitals (p. 202), and their treatment of a group of medical reservists (pp. 237-43) is painful to read. <br /><br />Many thanks to <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/4684009-william">https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/4...</a> for encouraging me to read this: I should have done so decades ago!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15380297724479711146" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


